We had two, a 94 with a 3.1 and a 96 with 3800. The 94 ended up with 140k before I gave it to a friend who was down on his luck, the 96 ended up with somewhere around 160k before I sold it. The only real issue was the Magnesium coolant fittings that would just fall apart resulting in hours of digging out of the intake to replace with brass.
GM throughout the early 90s was on that Magnesium kick that resulted it shit tons of parts that just disintegrated.
I honestly cant say I ever had many issues with them though.
Now the Toyota Previa that I bought for $1100 with 110k , I put another 200k on it, sold it to a buddy who put another 200k on it..lol

snippet.textDisplay: These vans (TranSport/Sillhouette/Lumina APV) were made of a composite material on the outside that was undentable.  The unibody cabin structure was one of the strongest of the time period.  The back overhead storage compartment was for CD's.  This overhead console was also used in top trim level Silverado's, Sierra's, Tahoe's and Suburban's (minus the two switches on the side).  They were marketed the minivan of the future, including the futuristic undentable body cladding.  The individual removable seats were also revolutionary 35 lb units, as the minivan seats from Chrysler group and FoMoCo were large heavy full row units that often required two people to remove them. I think these were the best looking FWD minivans made. (I classify the Astro/Safari vans as mid-sized vans, not minivans.  I think they also deserve a review, being no other mid-sized vans existed.)
snippet.textOriginal: These vans (TranSport/Sillhouette/Lumina APV) were made of a composite material on the outside that was undentable.  The unibody cabin structure was one of the strongest of the time period.  The back overhead storage compartment was for CD's.  This overhead console was also used in top trim level Silverado's, Sierra's, Tahoe's and Suburban's (minus the two switches on the side).  They were marketed the minivan of the future, including the futuristic undentable body cladding.  The individual removable seats were also revolutionary 35 lb units, as the minivan seats from Chrysler group and FoMoCo were large heavy full row units that often required two people to remove them. snippet.textDisplay:
My parents had a later version back when they were new.
They were dog show enthusiasts and needed the room for their German Shepherds.
It was also my mother's daily driver and over the course of their ownership it accumulated over 300k mostly trouble-free miles.
The interior and paint looked kinda shabby but it still ran perfectly and everything worked.
My father eventually sold it the father of one of his employees for $300.00.
He drove it from Wisconsin to Alaska and drove it for a few more years before he went down a rutted rocky back road and cracked the oil pan.
Didn't notice the oil pressure warning light until it was too late.
Last I heard it was still parked on his property with the passenger door open because he uses it as a dog house.
